.querySelector only selects the first instance if there are multiple classes with the same name.
.querySelectorAll selects all and puts them in a NodeList
Node list - like an array

for loops can have curly braces omitted, like an if statement, if you only have one line

.classList gives you options on what to do with the classes of an element. add, remove, etc. multiple classes can be listed with commas
  - dont use the dot to signify classes 
    - modal.classList.remove('hidden') <-- correct
    - modal.classList.remove('.hidden') <-- not correct

keyboard events are considered global events because they dont happen on one certain element.
keyboard events usually listen on the whole document

when and event is handled, JS creates an object that we can analyze to better understand what is going on
  - can do this by console logging the argument of the function